entries.meaning: (countable) A short, high-pitched sound, as of two objects rubbing together, or the sounds made by mice and other small animals.
(uncountable, games) A card game similar to group solitaire.

examples: "I had the very devil of a squeak for it," he went on. "I did the hurdles over two or three garden-walls, but so did the flyer who was on my tracks, and he drove me back into the straight and down to High Street like any lamplighter.  […]

verbs.description: squeak (third-person singular simple present squeaks, present participle squeaking, simple past and past participle squeaked)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To emit a short, high-pitched sound.

examples: If he be obstinate, put a civil question to him upon the rack, and he squeaks, I warrant him.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To speak or sound in a high-pitched manner.
(intransitive, games) To empty the pile of 13 cards a player deals to oneself in the card game of the same name.
(intransitive, informal) To win or progress by a narrow margin.
examples: […]  allowing Parkinson to squeak into the final by a half-point margin.
